title: Respond to a court claim for money

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
chunks.html_content:
You’ll get a letter or email if someone claims you owe them money. You must respond by the date on the email or letter you receive.

Follow the instructions in the email or letter. You should respond in the same way that the claim was made, for example you should respond online if the claim was made online.
chunks.plain_content:
Respond to a court claim for money
You’ll get a letter or email if someone claims you owe them money. You must respond by the date on the email or letter you receive.
Follow the instructions in the email or letter. You should respond in the same way that the claim was made, for example you should respond online if the claim was made online.

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
Ways to respond
chunks.html_content:
You can:

  • pay the full amount
  • offer to pay a different amount (if you think you owe less than the claim amount)
  • defend the claim (if you do not think you owe any money)

If you offer to pay a different amount and it’s rejected, you might have to give more information at a hearing.

You can ask for another 14 days to respond if you are not paying the full amount. You might have to pay more or get a county court judgment (CCJ) if you do not respond in time.

You can also make a claim against them (‘counterclaim’) if you think they owe you money. You might have to pay a court fee.

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
If the claim was made using the Online Civil Money Claims service
Get help using the Online Civil Money Claims service
chunks.html_content:
You’ll need to know which service was used to make the claim. Check your email or letter if you’re not sure.

You can use a paper form to respond instead if you cannot use the online service.

You’ll need to create an account to respond to the claim.

You’ll need your claim number and security code. Your claim number will include ‘MC’.

Respond using the Online Civil Money Claims service.

Contact Civil Money Claims.

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
After you’ve responded
chunks.html_content:
Keep proof (for example, your bank records or a receipt from the claimant) to show you’ve paid.

If you offer to pay a different amount, the claimant will decide whether to accept it. If you defend the claim, the claimant will decide whether to proceed or withdraw the claim.

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
If the claim is for a specified amount
chunks.html_content:
If the claim was made using a paper form, you should respond by post. You can also use a paper form to respond if the claim was made online but you are not able to use the online services. You’ll have received a letter with instructions on how to respond.

The forms you fill in will depend on whether the claim is for a fixed (‘specified’) or an unspecified amount. If you need more time to respond to the claim, download and fill in form N9.

Download and fill in:

  • form N9A to pay all or part of the claim
  • form N9B if you do not agree with the claim

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
Mediation organised by the court
The mediation appointment
chunks.html_content:
Mediation is when an impartial professional (the mediator) helps both sides work out an agreement. It’s confidential and usually quicker and cheaper than going to court.

The court may offer you mediation if you dispute the claim. You can also arrange independent mediation yourself.

The court will offer you mediation if you are disputing a claim of £10,000 or less. This service is free.

If both sides agree to mediation, a mediator from HM Courts and Tribunal Service (HMCTS) will speak to you separately by phone to help you to explore options, negotiate and agree a settlement.

Once both sides have agreed to mediation, you’ll be given a date and time for your telephone appointment. The appointment will last up to one hour.

You can bring someone with you to mediation. For example, a trusted friend, relative, or a solicitor.

Contact the small claims mediation service if you have questions about the claim or your appointment. Include your claim number with your query, if you have one.

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
Independent mediation
chunks.html_content:
You can get mediation from an independent mediator for a claim of any amount. There’s a fixed fee for this service.

If the claim is for £10,000 or less, you may also have to attend court mediation if independent mediation is unsuccessful.
chunks.plain_content:
Respond to a court claim for money
Independent mediation

If the claim is for £10,000 or less, you may also have to attend court mediation if independent mediation is unsuccessful.

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
If you reach an agreement
chunks.html_content:
You’ll make a verbal agreement at the mediation appointment. This is legally binding which means that you must follow it. You’ll be given the terms of the agreement in a document – this is called a settlement agreement.

If either side breaks the terms, then the other side can go to court to ask for a judgment or hearing.

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
If you do not reach an agreement
chunks.html_content:
You’ll have to attend a court hearing.

You cannot mention what happened during the mediation appointment in court.

You will not have to wait longer for a court hearing if you go to mediation first.

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
After the hearing
chunks.html_content:
You might have to give more information at a hearing if your offer is rejected or if mediation is unsuccessful.

If there’s a hearing, you can:

  • represent yourself
  • pay for a barrister or solicitor to represent you
  • ask someone to advise you in court - they do not have to be a lawyer
  • ask someone to speak on your behalf - you might need to get the court’s permission

Your hearing can be held in the judge’s room or a courtroom in a county court if the claim is for less than £10,000. There might be a more formal hearing if the claim is for more.

You’ll get a decision on the day of the hearing. The court will also send you a copy of the decision by post.

heading_context: Respond to a court claim for money
Appeal the decision
chunks.html_content:
You can ask to appeal the decision if you think the judge made a mistake during the hearing. You must ask within 21 days of the date the decision was made.

Find out which court or tribunal to appeal to.
